longest_values: Con Edison needs to gain access to MH63307 which is located inside Canarsie Park to dewater and then enter the structure to cut and cap (i.e. de-energize and abandon) three electric cables inside. No cables will be pulled from this manhole and no intrusive work is proposed. The proposed plan is to have a tanker truck on the adjacent property (pending access agreement) and run a hose over the fence and into the manhole (this is the shortest distance). The manhole is located in a vegetated portion of the Park. To provide safe access to the manhole, a small path would need to be cleared for the crew and their equipment. Con Edison is requesting authorization to clear a path approximately 3-ft wide to the manhole and around the structure. The duration of the work is approximately 2-3 days

As a part of Con Ed’s Overhead Reliability Initiative. Feeder 33R07 has substantial percentages of Paper Impregnated Lead Cable (PILC) and Corrugated Metal Polyethylene Finished (CMPF) type cable along the feeder route. Upon the loss of Feeder 33R07, contingency within the grid is compromised and the mobilization of generators would be required to alleviate any potential overloads or voltage issues.  A total of 2 miles of new aerial cable and 75 pole replacements will be undertaken as a part of the upgrade.  Within the Green Street area, two poles are proposed to be replaced and limited amount of trenching is also required between Pole 20672 and Manholes 7068 and 7067.

The purpose of this project is to improve safety deficiencies and restore pavement to good condition along the Harlem River Drive from the Metro North Railroad overpass at 133rd Street to 167th Street. The scope of work of this project includes: milling; resurfacing, and pavement marking of the Harlem River Drive mainline, ramps, and asphalt overlayed viaduct; median replacement and upgrade with single slope concrete barrier, median lampposts, and chain link fence; minor ground mounted sign and reference marker replacement; roadside guiderail barrier and appurtenances.

The scope of work includes the trenching (approximately 850' long x 7' wide x 7' deep) on the eastern sidewalk of Sedgwick Ave between Fort Independence St and Giles pl, to expose Con Edison's existing electric feeder pipes in service below the sidewalk to perform the needed feeder pipe coating maintenance and pipe repairs necessary for system reliability. As each section of feeder pipe repairs are completed new concrete sidewalk will be installed (8' wide) within the affected sidewalk area replacing the old concrete sidewalk.
Order of Sites: Pier 66 must be completed first. Following 66, work is to then proceed southward through the piers, with only one location occupied or worked on at a time.iii.
